Time between sexist crimes¶

Let's try something more serious. In 2020 43 gender-based violence crimes took place in Spain, this is, 43 women were murdered by their partners during this year:

https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020-03-27/cronologia-de-victimas-mortales-de-violencia-de-genero-de-2020.html

We will use an exponential distribution to explore the interval in days between sexual aggression events. The exponential distribution is a continuous probability distribution commonly used to model the time between events that occur continuously and independently at a constant average rate. In other words, the probability of an event occurring tomorrow does not depend on what happened yesterday. Because of this property, known as "memorylessness", the exponential distribution is often used to model catastrophic or rare events such as meteorite impacts, volcanic eruptions, or terrorist attacks. In our case, we will use it to model the days between sex crimes, assuming that the occurrence of one crime does not influence the timing of the next, there is no reason to think otherwise. The models output allows to estimate the average interval between crimes and assess the likelihood of a new crime occurring within a specific time frame.

We can therefore predict based on the distribution of the interval crime data which is the probability of a crime occuring as days go over. By the nature of the data, we should have an a priori exponentail distribution. Let's use dexp (desity distribution) and pexp The limit of dexp is 0, and the limit of pexp is 1 (this is, the possibility of having all random values).

$${ \lambda = \frac{1}{\overline{mean.interval}}}$$ 

If a random variable X follows an exponential distribution, then the probability density function of X can be written as
$${ dens.p=\lambda e^{-\lambda x} }$$

and therefore, the cumulative distribution function of X can be written as:

$${ cum.p=1-e^{-\lambda x} }$$

<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distribution>

The empirical cumulative distribution function (ECDF) provides a clear, data-driven view of the intervals between crimes. As expected, the ECDF is similar in shape to the exponential CDF, but as the name implies, it is purely empirical: it shows the proportion of observed intervals up to a given number of days, without assuming any underlying distribution.

The ECDF plot shows that more than 80% of crimes occurred within an interval of 15 days. This 80% figure is purely descriptive, derived directly from the observed data, without assuming any underlying distribution. It gives a clear picture of the timing of past events but does not provide a probabilistic estimate for future events beyond the observed intervals.

Interpretation:

dexp() returns the corresponding value of the exponential density for an input day. Still puzzles me is that the probability of an exact value must be 0 in theory. The easy answer is that is not the exact probability of any random value, but the probability density for that value, well, same counterintuitive think occurs for any density plot. This means that most crimes are centered in the first week, this is a really scary interval.

pexp() is the probability that the angry time is less than or equal than a certain value, the cumulated probability as days pass. So yes, this is a similar idea to the empirical probability density function (ECDF), only that the latter is the actual proportion of a value equal or less than a particular day, whereas the value of pexp here refers to a cumulated exponential probability distribution under the particular rate, lambda, in this case 1/7. This means, for example, that after a 2 weeks passed without a crime the probability of one ocurring goes above 80%, and after 20 days the probability of having a crime goes beyond 90%, so police should be really alert after this period.

Both dexp and pexp demonstrate the meaning of the exponential function, only that it does not go exponentially forever as the limit of dexp is 0, and the limit of pexp is 1 (this is, the possibility of having all random values), but wont never get to 1. On the contrary ecdf will get to the 100% of all values at the highest observed value.

$${ \lambda = \frac{1}{\overline{interval}}}$$

Predicted sex crime probability with confidence intervals¶

In [9]:
n <- length(crime.interval)
sum_x <- sum(crime.interval)

# 95% CI for lambda using chi-square
lambda_lower <- qchisq(0.025, df = 2*n) / (2 * sum_x)
lambda_upper <- qchisq(0.975, df = 2*n) / (2 * sum_x)

# Days to plot
days <- 0:90

# CDF (cumulative probability) and CI
cdf <- 1 - exp(-lambda_hat * days)
cdf_lower <- 1 - exp(-lambda_upper * days)  # note: upper lambda  lower probability
cdf_upper <- 1 - exp(-lambda_lower * days)  # lower lambda  upper probability

# Plot
plot(days, cdf, type = "l", lwd = 2, col = "blue",
     ylim = c(0,1), xlab = "Days", ylab = "Probability of at least one crime",
     main = "Cumulative probability of a crime over time")
polygon(c(days, rev(days)),
        c(cdf_lower, rev(cdf_upper)),
        col = rgb(0,0,1,0.2), border = NA)  # shaded CI
lines(days, cdf, col = "blue", lwd = 2)  # overlay main line

# Optional: add horizontal lines for key probabilities
abline(h = c(0.5, 0.9, 0.95), col = c("grey","orange","red"), lty = 2)

#add labels for 50%, 90% and 95%
text(20, 0.52, "50%", col = "grey", pos = 4)
text(50, 0.92, "90%", col = "orange", pos = 4)
text(70, 0.97, "95%", col = "red", pos = 4)

#can I have also a vertical line for the days corresponding to these probabilities?

Figure 14. Cumulative probability of at least one crime over time based on the exponential model fitted to observed intervals between crimes. The blue line shows the estimated cumulative probability (CDF) of a new crime occurring within a given number of days. The shaded blue area represents the 95% confidence interval for the CDF, calculated from the chi-square confidence interval for the rate parameter . Horizontal dashed lines indicate key probabilities (50%, 90%, and 95%), and vertical dashed lines show the corresponding number of days required to reach these probabilities.

This figure illustrates how rapidly the probability of a new crime increases over time, highlighting that most crimes are likely to occur within a relatively short interval. Lets have the estimated number of days for 50%, 90% and 95%:

In [13]:
lambda <- 1 / mean.c  # estimated rate

# probabilities
p <- c(0.5, 0.9, 0.95)

# corresponding number of days
days_p <- -log(1 - p) / lambda
days_p
  1. 5.17442430138936
  2. 17.1890654616532
  3. 22.3634897630426

Based on the exponential model fitted to the observed intervals between crimes, the estimated time until a new sex crime occurs increases rapidly at first and then more slowly, reflecting the nature of the exponential distribution. Specifically, there is approximately a 50% probability of a new crime within just 5 days, a 90% probability within 17 days, and a 95% probability within 22 days (Figure 14). This illustrates how quickly the risk accumulates over a short period, consistent with the short intervals observed in the empirical data.

Sample size¶

Here an interesting point, how much data do we need to have to have a representativa sample size. Well, the question is representative of what, if it is representative of a year, we actually collected the data in a year, it is what it is. But well say that the question is whether 1 year of data, this is, 43 crime intervals, are enough to represent what occurs during 10 years, a decade. Well, let's use our 1 year pilot study then where we have a mean interval, and say the error is the 3% of that mean... Thus cause we are assessing the mean time interval between crimes, which is 7.46 days, then a 3% allowable error would be 0.22 days (0.03 7.46). The formula for estimating the required sample size for a mean is:

$${ n=\frac{z^{2}\sigma ^{2}}{e^{2}} }$$

we can write it like this as well

$${ n=\left (\frac{z\sigma }{e} \right )^{2} }$$

but, where does this come from? I guess it comes from the notion of the confidence interval:

$${ z\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} }$$

so that the estimate is:

$${ \bar{x}\pm z\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} }$$

Note that S/n^2 is SE, the standard error

good explanation here: http://www.ub.edu/ceea/sites/all/themes/ub/documents/Tamano_muestral.pdf

In particular a 95% confidence interval of a mean estimate is given by the formula

Estimate 1.96 SE

but... how do we get from this to

$${ n=\frac{z^{2}\sigma ^{2}}{e^{2}} }$$

The formula for any standard error always contains n, the sample size. Therefore, if you specify the width of the 95% confidence interval, you have a formula that you can solve to find n.

https://www.statstutor.ac.uk/resources/uploaded/sample-size.pdf
